comment: This is not difficult, funny, easy to participant class.

The professor has an incredible calming presence with which makes learning much more enjoyable and easier. The one thing is that the difficulty of the class is sometimes very low and sometimes more advanced but I understand that it can be because of the various levels of English language skills of all students.
The teacher is concerned about the welfare of his students, always willing to improve. His class has a great impact on the community. Congratulations, an honor to be part of his students.

I've had the pleasure of taking classes with Brian, and it's been an amazing experience. He is professional, patient, and passionate about teaching. Each lesson is clear, engaging, and tailored to my needs. Highly recommend classes!

Thank you Brian for this class. I like the structure and handouts. Usually the lectures are more then 2 hours and they contain a lot of different topics, new words + Iinks to the root of words and their origin (which I find especially enriching lectures). I wish we have 5-minute brake after approximately 1 hour (before advanced vocabulary).

The class is very informative for non-native speakers. It covers basic/advanced vocabularies, grammar, idioms, reading and humor. I cannot believe this class is free with its context and quality and am truly grateful that I get to know this class!!! Thank you Brian.
He is very enthusiastic!

This class is designed for non-native English speakers. It's free, doesn't require registration, has no homework, and doesn't involve any paperwork. It's open to everyone, and all are welcome.
The professor is an excellent instructor with extensive experience, he'll be happy to answer any questions you may have. This class is helpful for everyone.
Amazing professor
The informal nature of Brian's class makes participants feel at ease. He is a dedicated tutor who is attentive and does his best to answer all questions thoroughly.

I like the class. It is very much helpful for me

Thank you for your time! Is very help full.

His English class is well organized, from vocabulary, grammar to some formal text and cartoon language. Informative for non-native people. Materials are provided as color-printed handouts. I like this class.

Eventhough today was my first class I can say he is a great teacher. One of the best english class IÂ´ve ever attended. He really cares about the material and you can tell he really enjoys what he does. So good to have found his class!

Her lectures lack any objectivity and balance of both sides of an issue. They are an ongoing, disorganized spewing of her opinions based on outdated references. Professor Bogan is a hero among women. She is the successful lady economist of your dreams. She is a brilliant lecturer and patient and fair in office hours. Take all of her classes, fantastic for Public Economics and American Economic History.

I took 101 followed by 102, and I devised this strategy: Ignore the textbook. Go to lecture. (Though a friend did the opposite and got OK grades, too.) This was one of the unsung changed-my-life classes, not because it made me scrap my plans and become an economist but because I used it and thought about it every single day from then on.

comment: This course was better than previous. But she's still horrendous. Cannot believe I took her for this semester and the following.
Fantastic professor, my favorite in Economics so far!
Bogan is a good lecturer and a helpful teacher. She's a lovely professor to have, but be ready for some less-than-perfectly written exams and a worthless textbook.

Professor Bogan is amazing.  She inspired me to become an Economics major - even though it was not an easy - and inspired me to pursue a career in business.  She is an great professor and advisor, as well as a tremendous role model for women pursuing a career in Economics, Finance and business.
She was my professor at FDU 28 years ago and was BY FAR the best professor I ever had, left me with a life long passion for economcis
Love love love Bogan. Favorite Professor of all time. She is seriously smart. Changed my whole outlook in Princeton and after. My thesis was influenced by her love of monetary policy.

Beth Bogan made me love economics when I was dreading having to take it. Found her lectures crystal clear and interesting, and she's one of the most approachable professors I've ever had. Ended up taking a lot more econ. One of my absolute favorite profs ever.
Boring but nice
Took her class 25 years ago at a different school....she is who inspired me to go into economics and finance...
She's a bit boring, but definately well intentioned. Her  lecture slides which are available online are very good so you don't really have to go to class.

not good

takes a boring subject and makes it even more boring. zzz....

great preceptor, very nice lady, great dinner conversation

you know, i hate sound pissy, but i can't stand her lectures. i never showed up to class after the first two days since she puts the note on blackboard. it's just that she isn't as entertaining as Reinhart

Brilliant lecturer. Engages students in a large lecture. Examines both sides to arguments and leaves his personal politics outside the classroom. A wonderful experience.
Amazing teacher.  Fair. Honest.  Brilliant.  Cares about students.

A must for students who want a real education. The constitutional issues discussed would interest any modern American. This course makes students think with the clarity one should expect to have on leaving college. Professor George is rightly known for his fairness, interest in his students, and his love for lively but respectful debate.

Professor George's courses on constitutional interpretation and civil liberties are a must for any Princeton student interested in responsible citizenship. I've heard so many people remark that while their personal interests lie outside of politics, George's classes taught them the kind of critical thinking necessary for a democracy to thrive.

By far one of the best classes I took at Princeton. Professor George does an excellent job of challenging students to articulate both sides of the issue.  His classes equipped me with the intellectual tools to critically evaluate controversial issues from all angles.
One of the best classes I had at Princeton.  Professor George challenged us to examine our beliefs, no matter what they were.  Talented lecturer and excellent material.
Professor George was the best teacher I encountered at Princeton.  He led terrific class discussions, and really stretched students to consider alternate points of view.
One of my best professors at Princeton.  Hard but fair.

I suspect that the two hateful comments in this thread weren't written by Princeton students; all the Princeton students I know can express their opinions in a more grownup fashion.  Professor George's courses were the two best of my entire time at Princeton.  His clarity, civility, and eye-opening insight changed the course of my academic career.

This is the best professor I ever had.  Because of this class, I majored in the Politics department at Princeton, and went on to a top law school.  I still remember things he said when he taught.  This is THE top Professor at Princeton.

Congenial, deadly brilliant, unassuming, provocative, necessary for a complete Princeton experience. His liberal colleagues have only the highest respect for him and have given him the country's most respected constitutional law chair. 'Nough said.
really smart and clear

As a true-blue liberal, I must say that I LOVED his classes -- what an eye-opener!  He's brilliant, probably the best professor I've ever had, and single-handedly impacted my career decisions. Take the course, be prepared to do worse than you might in other classes -- you will definitely benefit.
Take only if you have the stones to be shocked out of your blue state bigotry. RG is smart and provocative. He will shatter your complacency.
One of the best reasons to go here. Intelligent and insightful.

classes and reading are generally thought-provoking and balanced, but he is a bit of a prima donna. a lot depends on your preceptor (avoid oakley)

Was my single most significant class at Princeton - and I'm in CS/EE!  Thanks, Prof. George.
Best class I've ever taken... also the hardest

I can't believe Robbie George has such a low rating here. Sure his class is hard and he has conservative politics and whatever else, but the man is an ultra-genius. Con Interp was the only lecture I never missed in my four years at Princeton. Prof. George is spellbinding, and the Princeton experience is incomplete without one of his classes.

To the person who criticized Prof. George's teaching ability based upon his authorship of the proposed protection of marriage constitutional amendment: it's 'amendment,' one 'm', not two. Who was your spelling teacher? And, for that matter, your intro to logic prof? Both deserve to be censured.
Once you worked with Andrea, you would believe all the other negative reviews are true.

Your research is a function of your advisor's active research profile. I do not know about the past. But these days with Andrea, you will probably work with one of her collaborators on an average problem or end up completing your PhD working on an inconsequential problem. Do not expect her for any guidance or her support after you graduate.

The language of the reviews for profs at UIUC,  U Mich, USC, UC, etc is identical, indicating a single reviewer. It dont make any sense. You could set up a web forum for supporting PhD students with  peer support, mental health support, etc that would be so helpful. Please flag your reviews of  professors and remove them. I dont flag them anymore.

And I don't think you actually ever worked with Andrea to know anything how she operates yet u r just trying to save her. Just do an exercise and ask any of her current/past students/postdocs. It is very common knowledge that she doesn't work with you and mostly spends time in politics or elsewhere. And if this is true see what you are defending.

I think u r wrongly assuming it is 1 person who is writing all these reviews. I wrote a couple for Andrea and thats it. Even many here are not written by me and apart from Poor/Javidi (after you mention), I don't know who all these Profs r that u r tracking. U should reexamine ur assumption that only one person is writing bad reviews for everybody

I think there are a LOT of very good Profs who genuinely care about their students, who treat them very well and more, help them much after graduation, and i am ALL for reporting positive reviews for such. I can myself name sooo many who are excellent advisors and would recommend students to work for them including many at Princeton ECE.

If your advisor was unethical, u should complain to the university  which has effective ways to deal with this. Professors are fired for unethical behavior.  Why unjustly attack more than 6 professors on RMP? Dont make sense. Either u are a troll or u have mental health issues; if latter, please get help. Most of your flagged reviews were removed.

I don't think you arent really answering why if a person has a negative experience can not report a negative review. Why it has to be positive. Do you know how costly it is to have a bad advisor, or someone who mentally harasses you or like Andrea just doesn't meet and is only into politics and no research? Do students' lives have no value?

Right! RMP cleared many of these reviews & let them decide.I can only say for Andrea not for others but I do stand for their rights to report a review if they feel mistreated. U r assuming ALL profs care about students (many do) but many don't and it is totally legit to review them here. And people should report +ve PhD experiences also(as they do)

I don't see why it is one sided-- they can ask for our reference letters, but then if they treat students bad, why cant students make a review about it? is it only competitive for them and not for the students? and if it is competitive for them, is it ok to mistreat students? There are soooo many contradictions in this persons arguments

I think this person just has a problem with the idea that people should not report negative reviews about profs for their PhD experience even if they had terrible experience. I don't know how they admit such morons (if he/she is actually ever admitted to one of these universities)

If you can buy a pizza and if you don't like it, you can leave a bad review, I don't know in what world you spend five best years of your life, have a bad experience and it is not ok to leave a bad review.

Who defines RMP is *only* for courses. Why do people not have a right to report a bad PhD experience? Do people not have bad experiences or is it just not ok to report it? Flunked or not, a student is *also* a venture capitalist who is putting her life in the system and if is treated badly has all the right to report it (the least she can do)

RMP is used to rate  professors teaching a specific course - not to defame a professor because u flunked a PhD. Writing multiple nasty reviews (>50 for Javidi, >20 for Goldsmith) is unethical. An advisor is not a parent. An advisor is  a venture capitalist that invests in the best PhD  students to achieve success in a highly competitive world.

This +ve reviewer is putting the same defense for Andrea as that prof from UW Madison did when his grad student ended his life. He said the student was a loner. Do loners not get to live? Do students who were "kicked out" (per the violent language used by the +ve reviewer) supposed to keep silent about the prof who mistreated them?

Even a student who was kicked out of UC, as this +ve reviewer claims, has every right to make his/her opinions known. A failure of a student in a PhD program is also a shared failure of his/her mentor. Beware of those professors who shrug off their responsibility in students' failures and claim credit only for the students' successes.

Absolutely! Prof. Goldsmith, Javidi, Poor and all other profs suggested by the +ve reviewer below are as good as this reveiwer. It would help to put these amazing profs in a list and for people who believe this reveiwer to join them to experience them themselves. Prof Javidi's IT video is inspirational.

Just chill people! The positive reviewer probably has a professional debt to pay to his master. Defending her here to show how loyal he or she is to Andrea. Strange that this reviewer says other reviewers are unemployed but comes here daily to rant. Sad to be reduced to this than focus on his/her own research.

comment: He is a terrible professor. Avoid his classes.

It's honestly pretty shocking to me that this many people hated him this much. He's really overhated and I didn't find him coming off as pretentious at all. He has a weird grading criteria, but other than that he's just thorough with paper feedback. He'll challenge you if he disagrees, but you can defend yourself, and it's not hostile at all.

He is really the worst kind of professor to have in college. Nothing is perfect, you can revise and revise your work and he will still have something negative to say. Fostered a hostile atmosphere with his attitude and behavior. Not a single person taking 315 this semester enjoyed themselves. It could have been a great class but he ruined it.

I went to office hours once and left in tears because he made me feel stupid and belittled. For our final wants us to have a record of every class we attended and participated in, but failed to let us know this at the beginning of the year that this was expected of us. If he doesn't like ONE thing about your paper, he marks it as incomplete. AVOID!

I am a student at American University. He is the worst professor I have ever taken and I will never take another class with him. He is arrogant and dismissive.  He presents instead of teaches as a result his class has been a massive waste of my time. He is unnecessarily punitive and is having us report every time we've spoken in class.

I was nervous to take his class after the reviews but he was super supportive and caring as a Professor. Definitely seemed to have received feedback of some form from the University. There was definitely a lot of reading, but that is expected for a 400 level class. Wish I could have taken another class from him before I graduated.

comment: While there was a lot of reading required for this course (expected for a 400 level class), I definitely learned a lot and it was all very interesting. very bias and too opinionated in lecture courses.  i wouldn't call her 'even handed,' and find it surprising that so many people credit her for her moderate point of view - her lectures suggest otherwise.  Doran would be a better representation of moderate.

Professor Rose is very passionate about genetics and it shows - however, the level of difficulty of this course is huge - from the mind-breaking problem sets to the ridiculously long exams (i.e. exams are so long that it feels as if you are not really being tested on your knowledge but rather on how fast you can interpret complex data)
Nice
No Comments
Strongly recommended.
Most Students usually find her classes not too hard because she as actually really good at teaching.
Professor Gmachl is awesome and extremely smart.
great guy but watch out for cos 109 - its not an easy A, and i had to work hard. the concepts are really difficult, but he's a great guy.

This guy is really a gem.  He's so humble that you wouldnt even know that he's a huge figure in the history of programming.  He flat out knows his stuff yet is the most kind and helpful professor I have ever met, unbelievable class.
Kernighan's a genius. He's amazingly friendly and clear. He makes computers accessible to the liberal arts brain and makes you want to wake up in the morning.
Extremely boring lectures, poor teaching.
Made me lose my interest in Economics.. basically self-taught the entire course, going to lecture was pretty pointless.
strong latin accent and very fast speech requires strict attention but still very very hard to fully understand even with microphone on. Young and very attractive and very smart and prepared.

COL Miles was my instructor for Grand Strategy in the 20th Century and later, my thesis advisor.  An inspiring warrior-scholar of the highest order, with deep insight into the people, events, and context that shape the modern world. He was the best teacher ever.   I still carry 3x5s, always take a position and engage in a social sport.

Took his Vietnam seminar my senior spring and it was one of the best classes at Princeton. He's been around for forever so he's got his teaching act down cold. Plus he remembers EVERYTHING and is incredibly knowledgeable. An awesome professor.
No Comments
He's so hot.  Also, he is brilliant and clear and funny. Take his class! Easy.
Sometimes his lectures were too slow, if anything, but it made sure we knew the material very well. Our precept discussions were fascinating and sometimes very comical.
Really funny.

Now in WashU StLouis and is definitley the worst professor I came across in my 4 years at this uni. Her slides are confusing and terms are not explained clearly. Homework quizzes gravitate wildley from her lecture slides.

Not good at teaching. Reading off slides in class but her slides are not helpful and not explanatory at all. I can only reference to them to know what are some major terms or issues that I should know when self-studying at home. Be prepared to study a lot by yourself and read books very carefully.
She is absolutely awful. Extremely rude and unwilling to help. Avoid her at ALL costs.
Janos is a baller. His office hours are phenomenal and he is more than willing to help with any question whatsoever. Professor Kollar is excellent.
Such an awesome instructor! Don't fall asleep in class, though. He'll get you for it (well not really, but you'll feel like an idiot).
No Comments
this is from a couple years ago - he no longer teaches.  I was just reflecting on how such an insanely gifted and hardworking man still took the time to be a wonderful teacher.
Professor Avinosh is very helpful. Clarity is apparent in his classroom. But....the best part of being in class is looking at his beautiful face.
No Comments
Professor Gleason went out of his way to choose material that was important but a little off the beaten path, and he really worked with his students to help us understand and think critically.
Best professor ever! I hear his son is really cool too!!!!

Wonderful instructor--his lectures are equally accessible to majors and non-majors alike, which can be a rarity in this department. Gleason selects great reading material and does an excellent job of orienting students by explaining the historical context of the books on which he lectures. This approach is really effective--take his course!
shes cool
She's great, very knowledgeable & approachable
No Comments
so cool and hip and contemporary & pc

I dropped White's class after only a week -- it was that painful.  His response to every question -- even the most legitimate ones -- was, "who knows?"  Apparently not him -- don't waste your time on this rubbish.
Very cosmopolitan; gives feedback pretty gently but informatively. Great lit taste!
best decision you could ever make
No Comments
Funny lady. Good teacher. Very nice.

Prof Chavel is clearly one of the most caring and devoted professors in the field. He is always available, open to talk, interested in how you're processing the material, and such. He is quick to respond as well; He is really a model professor and made learning about the HB exceedingly interesting. HOWEVER, he is NOT easy, and that is a GOOD THING
This class is enthralling. We are all completely transfixed and enchanted by his lectures. Prof. Chavel is the best professor at Princeton.
No Comments
Professor Gavis is a great professor who teaches with clarity and goes at an appropriate pace. Would definitely take a class with her again.

Professor Gavis is one of the best professors that I have had at Princeton. She delivers amazing lectures that introduce students to the complexity of molecular biology - she expects excellent work from her students and constant critical thinking - All in all, she pushes you to learn and think like a scientist
she was amazing!

Princeton Algorithms is the best algorithm course you can find on our planet. The professor constructed this course and its textbook carefully and perfectly. The PDF really helps me a lot not only in the course but also future careers. Take and try it ! Princeton Algorithms YYDS!!
loving his coursera course. very clear, unassuming, and unpretentious.
bob sedgewick is the only computer scientist you will ever need
Fantastic
His orgo notes are really helpful. not to mention his handwriting is amazing
Best orgo professor ever!!!

Vince is actually a nice person. My low rating is because of his recent spate of "paper-milling" (ie, producing incremental publications en masse, without thorough research). As a postdoc or grad student, working with him at this stage can be detrimental to your career.

Did you notice Poor has papers now on every topic in EE (and beyond)? COVID, blockchain, cryptocurrency, water management, marketing, metaverse, economics, power systems. LOL! His polymath abilities would put even Leonardo da Vinci to shame.
I didnt write the reviews below but i have a question: these 240+ papers are legit then, written by him at his age where most well established profs are writing at max 10-15 papers in a year ?
Amazing professor! Favorite of my time here.
He is not at all helpful and does not take arguments and other points of view positively.  Lost all my interest in the topic!
I learned to go from translating to reading
Outstanding professor. Ford is a blast to have class with: he's helpful and energetic, but he's a difficult grader.

I really liked that the class wasn't confined to an only speak Arabic rule. English was used sparingly but only when it is was most useful, and that helped me learn a lot more effectively. Anita has a lot of tricks to help students pronounce letters well and remember words. Great class - Anita was always available and very patient. -

Amazing professor! She makes sure to go over material  until students are able to grasp it. Her in-class activities are always very interactive and actually a lot of fun since she interweaves Arabic language with Arabic culture. She also gives feedback on all homework and testsquizzes. She is very helpful and her passion for Arabic is infectious!
very hard lot of homework
The material is super interesting, but the class is pretty tough.
She's dedicated, interesting, passionate, and so so cool. Really awesome research, taught a fascinating class, all around great professor.
great class and she is hot
Lectures were super helpful and easy to understand

comment: Took Intro to Moral with Frick last Spring. He's horrible. Avoid him at all costs.

As a professor, just restating what the book says, lectures useless. As a review for the final test he told the preceptors that the only thing they were allowed to tell us about the short answer test was that it contained short answers.
No Comments
Good guy; can be difficult to understand what he's looking for at times.  Very passionate about his subject.  Frustrated by immaturity (very understandably). Will challenge you to push yourself.
nice guy.  hard grader.  can sometimes be a little abstract and hard to understand exactly what he's looking for but he'll keep trying to answer your question.
He is very much interested in the learning of his students and his lectures are by far the most exciting and interesting at Princeton

Mr. Oppenheimer is quite possibly one of the best teachers at Princeton.  He is eager to teach his students, is willing to get involved with their studies and loves his subject.  He is funny, caring and overall a very awesome professor.

Best professor I ever had. Took his class freshman fall, made me want to change my major to History or Politics because he made the material so interesting. His lectures were one big story, you didn't want to miss anything.
Smart and dynamic. Engaging lecturer. His class made me want to be a history major.

He's a good teacher and he makes an effort to ensure everyone understands the material. He had short office hours but was flexible with scheduling appointments outside office hours. Overall a really good teacher for an intro to a foreign language.
No Comments
Our entire campus is absolutely obsessed with her.

Dr. V is probably the best thing that has ever happened to me. She's an amazing Professor who doesn't belittle you simply because you're a student. She seeks to understand you ideas rather than shut them down like many other professors. She's a gem, adorable, and introverted which makes her all the more genuine. Her office hours are a great help!!!

Dr. Quinn is an amazing professor. Even if you are not a theater fan the way she teaches her class will make you fall in love with the art of theater. She gives amazing feedback and makes you feel like part of her family. She never forgets a student, and if you need anything she will always be there for you. Amazing person and amazing professor!

Dr. Quinn is an amazing professor. Very talented in her subject. Her classes are always very interesting and she wants to help her students in any way possible. Take her class and you won't be disappointed.
Dr. Grafton is one of the best lecturers you will have at Princeton. Never miss the chance to take any of his classes.

Grafton. Is. God.  His lectures are the most amazing thing you will ever be blessed to hear. That said, TAKE HIS CLASS. Even if all you need is a history requirement, taking his class would be doing yourself a favor and experiencing one of the best lectures at Princeton.
Very organized class. The professor is attentive to methodological issues in the history discipline and always listens to student's thoughts.

Class super easy. Assignments were not helpful to learning the material. Made us write a wikipedia entry on China without any potentially problematic political statements - almost impossible. Did not know how to answer questions in class and tried to brush them off with commonplace assertions on China.
What a great professor!
Good man. Has a lot of critters. Go to office hours. He will rock your world.

Great class. She makes lectures and references to the textbook clear. Only problem is that it is rather hand-wavy at times but perhaps this is understandable, since it is an introductory class. Good introduction to computer vision. I would recommend this class to new-comers.
Great class
Hot
I luv u!! Emily?

Mahiri really challenged my preconceived notions about Africa in a way I was not expecting. We read the same literature everyone reads about the continent, but examined how and why those narratives persist to he tshape dominant discourse on Africa. Mahiri is a professor to take if you want the real deal.
Mahiri is the best.

It's difficult to discern in Li any real interest in his students' success; his primary motivational tools are guilt and shame, worse as he doesn't know the difference between the two. An accomplished and skilled researcher who has produced truly seminal work, Li completely lacks empathy and can never be an effective mentor. That said, I did learn.
Not very clear lecturer

Probably one of the greatest teachers I've had in a while. She knows how to keep the class interactive and knows and explains the material effectively. Very sweet and naturally very funny as well. You have to do a lot of presentations but it is a speech class
The best professor I have had in my career at Princeton! He should teach physics to ALL students!

Prof. Fleischer is the man!  Very smart and cool prof.  He moves at a fast pace and expects a lot from you.  His tests are challenging, and focus mostly on physical understanding.  He's a very fair grader and is always willing to help you.  His class is like a complete education in itself!
This guy was plain AWFUL!
Worst professor I've had in my four years at Princeton!!
Sylvia is clueless about architecture and design, a pseudo intellectual posing in her best Marni outfits
so trash

Professor Zhu inspires one to think out of the box.
Good
Difficult grader, but your writing skills improve tremendously after this course.
Terrible. Rambles. Unprepared. Unclear. Ugh.

Kuenne's class is truly lacking in educational value. What you learn: definitions to questionable entrepreneurship buzz-concepts (e.g. "Minimum Viable Product") and vague, cliched business maxims (e.g. "have a vision"). Case method is laughable, assignments are unavailing and participation awarded subjectively. Avoid this class.
Doug Clark is a good lecturer, but isn't too important to the COS 126 class. Whereas precepts are critical, I found lectures to be fairly skippable.
Luis made Spanish class super fun. I learned a lot and although he expected a decent amount of work, he was very understanding and helpful. This class was great.
Absolute genius.
Elga is VERY succinct - he does not parse words, and he lets you know EXACTLY what you need to do for the papers/assignments.  Very approachable.
He was great!

Professor Pufu is very knowledgeable and explains complex topics thoroughly with very little loss of clarity. He also adapts to students' varying levels of understanding, not becoming frustrated if he must explain a simpler concept in much depth. Last, but of utmost importance, is his wicked sense of humor and profound suitability for being memed.
Professor Moritz Lenel may be very knowledgeable in economics, but the way he teaches is perplexing. It seems that the class can be better structured and be more applicable to industry.
Generally enjoyable, and the curriculum was very simple

Zhang laoshi is the best!

He is a great lecturer! His notes and explanations are super clear. The exams are hard and long, but you learn a lot.

comment: I took Comparative Animal Physiology with Ouyang and UNR and the class was interesting but she covered a ton of information and gave NO clear guidelines for what was actually important or what you were going to be tested on. comment: Prof. Slowinska is by far the best Arabic lecturer I ever had. She is wholeheartedly dedicated to her teaching and students, very enthusiastic and has a superb teaching style unlike other Arabic instructors who in my opinion are a bit overrated. She is one of those who make me proud to be Princetonian!
Funny guy, but not very clear about what he wants. Didn't develop a personal relationship with any of the students. Also, acted like he was just mailing in the class. It was unorganized.

Professor Teardo was outstanding... I took her Italian 101 class and loved it! She was understanding, caring, a great teacher, and even tried to make class fun. She made Italian my favorite class at Princeton. Looking forward to (at least) one more Italian of semester with her!
Fantastic professor. Very clear lecturer, interesting prompts, good feedback, and extra tidbits to keep you interested. Tough grader, but it's absolutely worth it.
Cool!
Impossible to work with
Mikki is super good. One of the best people out there. Great person, great work. Super reccomended

Great tutor for someone tutoring 4 classes. Harsh grader, though. He has the biggest heart and is very forthcoming. I wish he didn't swear as much, but it adds to the class humor. It kind of makes us less stressed out, but the fact that he looks so young did stress out the class at first.

Every day with Professor Snow is fun, but he knows how to be serious when he has to, and those were the moments I learned the most! 
Recommend his classes for everybody, but remember to feed him.

Professor Snow T-Shirt is an enigmatic gem in the Philosophy and Chaos Theory departments.

I took his class on Chaos Theory and the Philosophy of Entropy, with a minor focus on Ottomanism, and wow. He doesn't fill the room with a lot of words, but every sentence he does deliver has an uncanny weight, as if he's been holding onto it for nine lives.
Knows his stuff!

Margaret has a good demeanor in lectures, is respectful, and invites questions from students but fails to answer them adequately, contradicting herself at times. Her materials are not ordered well to group appropriate topics, and her tests/quizes do not fairly reflect what was mentioned in lectures or what was in the course materials (hand-outs).
Bernasek is amazing! He's so nice and he's a good lecturer too!

Took his social psychology class.  Prof. Taylor is quite the character and does a good job explaining the material in an engaging way.  A bit flaky sometimes in terms of communication, but never mean and often very helpful.
yes
Amazing lecturer.
Take his class if you want to get an in-depth knowledge of the field. He is a great guy and one of the best teachers around. Be prepared to work very hard.
Excellent teacher
An inspiration to students!

Professor De Oliveira is such a caring and understanding teacher. He is sympathetic and understands if people want to extend deadline. His grading policy is reasonable and he gives really good feedback on your drafts. While there is a lot of writing (it is a writing seminar!), he makes the topic very interesting. He also gives amazing writing tips!
Very smart and very funny, too.
Tough but fair.

comment: She is very helpful and is genuinely interested in what students have to say during class discussions.
Excellent lecturer, and an all around great guy.

Professor Nguyen is really helpful. If you don't get anything in class, GO TO OFFICE HOURS. He's always there to help you with whatever you need. He's not out to get you; he wants you to do well and most of his class does do pretty well. You need to put work into it, but if you study and work with him he will help you succeed.
Amazing professor and great guy. Makes really interesting and comprehensive lectures.

Fun and interesting discussions. Do all the readings, they're wonderful. Prof. Pagels is engaging and approachable. She has a very specific, Westernized/liberal view of religion which I often found frustratingly limited.
Flower was an outstanding lecturer, and he was very accessible during office hours.
He's a great lecturer.  He seems to expect a lot from students, and has a hard time hiding his disappointment, but he's very energetic and inspired.  That energy rubs off on students.
Genuinely excited about his material and willing to help you out if you should ever need it, although the course I took from him was ridiculously easy.
Hard work!

Completely useless--was clearly making things up as she went along, and hadn't even done the reading she herself had assigned. She got flustered when challenged. Is this really the much-vaunted "education" Princeton offers?
Interesting lectures, he opens leaves you with more questions than answers, but still an excellent Professor.
she aieet

Professor Dasgupta is great! He's clear and interesting in explanations, has a very specific but incredibly helpful grading system, and made me think a lot about the philosophy of science without feeling overloaded with work.

As one of inventors of AdaBoost (one of famous machine learning algorithm), prof. Robert is the right man to teach AI. He shows a role model that a professor can achieve both teaching and research in top level. His lecture is polish. He makes students enjoy AI algorithms and programming assignments rather than be a coding dog.

You should not expect Natalie to know more about corporate finance than you do when you register for the class. Her expertise is household finance and doesn't know much about corporate finance. Always enthusiastic to take questions in class, but never replied after class. Not available for questions before exams...
Good teacher
Blah
One of the kindest, most accessible, and helpful professors I've ever had. She led our seminar incredibly well and knew how to select good readings.

Professor Aksay was undoubtedly the best professor I've had so far at Princeton. CBE Thermodynamics is an insanely hard class, but he put an incredible amount of effort into teaching, and it really showed. His lectures are fantastic, HW assignments are hard but helpful, and exams are extremely fair. He also handpicks actually useful TA's.
She is super smart. Makes otherwise incomprehensible texts as clear as day. Also chill, kind and has a sense of humor.

Lectures are very clear.  Lots of examples.  Also, Professor Lorig is very entertaining.  He jokes a lot.  But, it doesn't distract from the class.  Homework solutions could be more clearly written.  I'd definitely take another class from Professor Lorig.
great guy. always helpful
No Comments

Ramadge is amazing. Very clear lecturer and cares a lot about student learning. Be warned that ECE 435 is no joke. Get ready to dive in (and really understand) MVC, linear algebra and optimization theory. Recommended for students whose goal is to learn and build solid mathematical foundations  not to get an A.

comment: Clear and animated - easy to listen and pay attention to
